##800 pieces of the shelter hospital puzzle

Wechat, bingdianweekly

Features, China Youth Daily's in depth reporting brand. We believe that news has more than one day of life.

On the afternoon of Feb. 4, more than 200 beds and mattresses were laid out in the main hall of the Wembley Arena, waiting for patients to move in. The Shelter Hospital provides a total of about 800 beds. China Youth Daily China Youth Net Trainee Reporter, Lu Chong / photo

This article is about 8040 words long

Estimated reading time: 21 minutes

Author | China Youth Daily, China Youth Daily, Wang Jiaxing

Editor | from Yuhua

Hongshan Stadium in Wuhan, built 34 years ago, became a hospital for the first time. The landmark, which has hosted such luminaries as the Tigers, Jonathan Lee and NBA stars, has housed up to 800 patients a month.

Zhang Bing, 48, brought his daughter here to learn to swim and worked as a security guard at a Richard Clayderman concert. He was familiar with the stadium, but he never thought he would one day live there as a patient for 15 days.

On February 3,2020, the Wembley Arena became one of the first 32 shelter hospitals planned or built in Wuhan to be converted into a new, less severe form of pneumonia. About 50,000 people have been diagnosed with new pneumonia in this city of more than 10 million people.

In the Wembley Arena alone, Han Chinese medical teams from Hebei, Liaoning, Hunan, Qinghai and Guangxi were stationed. On this cold winter's Day, thousands of patients crowded into the EAVES and began a "bed-to-bed" social life.

Meet

It took Wembley Arena less than 48 hours to prepare for the first wave of patients.

At 1:00 am on February 4, Liu Lianmei was asleep when she received a phone call from the hospital informing her of an emergency assembly. She is the head nurse of the Emergency Department of Huzhu Tu Autonomous County Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine in Qinghai Province and often rushes to the hospital in the middle of the night.

The call did not specify matters, but she and her husband vaguely felt that they might be trying to help Wuhan, so he drove her. Liu Lianmei and four colleagues were assigned to the Hubei Medical Team at 3 a.m. and assembled at 8 a.m.

Liu's 5-year-old son had woken up before setting out. Faced with the question of "where will my mother go? " Liu Lianmei said, "my mother will go far away to study, and you will listen to her grandparents at home. " Thinking that she might have to cut her hair short, she added, "My mother may have to cut her hair like yours to study, " said Liu's husband, who works in a detention center, the next day.

Liu Lianmei arrived in Wuhan, only to know that he had to support the "shelter hospital. ". She had only heard the word on the news, didn't know the concept, and had never seen the pictures. She had no idea she was about to face "an entire gym full of patients" .

By the time she got the call, the first group of 27 commandos from China's Wembley Arena, thousands of miles away, had already begun their work, and some workers had just arrived from the construction site of the quake mountain hospital. In less than 48 hours, the first patients will arrive at the shelter.

Final preparations are underway at 11 pm on February 5th, with the first patients arriving in half an hour. Electrician Chu Haining has not slept for 34 hours, after a short break, he began the basement of the stadium wiring work. Hundreds of medics in "China Health" uniforms marched in from his side, wires still strewn around their feet. Dozens of workers are urgently installing fences to divide clean and contaminated areas.

Dozens of porta-potties have just been installed at the other side of the stadium. The toilets are pitch black and have no lights; pools to sterilise the waste of patients are still under construction.

The shelter has been cleared. Four staff members at Xiangya Second Hospital in Hunan Province put on protective clothing in the cleaning area, only to find there were no goggles, called for emergency help, and finally borrowed from the medical team of Mount Hua Hospital in Shanghai. These goggles were meant for the four medics who were due to take over in six hours.

The ambulance is transporting the patient. Doctors sit in makeshift tents outside the stadium during a pre-diagnosis session in the bleak wind and rain. A doctor's underwear was soaked in sweat and quickly chilled by the wind because the suit was not breathable.

On February 2, Wuhan offered to lock up and segregate "four categories" of people. Around February 5, a large number of confirmed patients remained under home quarantine.

It was the most desperate moment for 46-year-old Fang Lei. Her father-in-law had been bedridden for two weeks, barely able to eat, and the family had searched far and wide for a bed. February 5, father-in-law confirmed the new crown pneumonia, before also harbors a Silk Fluke Fang Lei at the moment a black, "a family all can't escape. "

A few days later, her mother-in-law, her 11-year-old daughter, Xiao Meng, and herself were diagnosed.

Chen Jun, 45, was hospitalized at the Zhongnan Hospital in Wuhan. He had been running a fever of 39 C for nearly a week and had a blood oxygen level below 90% at one point. No intubation, no steroids, he made it out of there. He's up and about. Chen Jun occasionally reads the news and knows that many patients with far more serious conditions have no way to be hospitalized.

The I.C.U. has Chen in a state of depression. Several of his fellow patients in the ward were hooked up to suction machines all day long, without turning over and barely speaking. In the dead of night, there was only the "tick-tock" of the Ward Monitor, the heavy sucking and groaning of the patients. Chen Jun presses voice to cough, seldom get out of bed to move about, be afraid to affect a patient friend.

A few days later, he was transferred from central South Hospital to the Shelter Hospital. Chen Jun saw that some netizens said that the shelter hospital was a "Noah's Ark" . He liked the metaphor very much. "before, I was in a panic. When I came to the shelter, I felt saved. "

Zhang Bing was notified just after midnight on February 6 that he would be admitted to the shelter hospital. "I'm just happy to hear the Word Hospital, whatever it is, " he said. He has had a fever since Jan. 27 and is caring for his mother-in-law, who is also sick. Those days, they are in the hospital infusion, a line for a whole day. On the afternoon of February 5, he contacted the bed and took his mother-in-law to the hospital.

At 3 a.m. on Feb. 6, he was picked up by a bus and driven overnight into a shelter. All he remembered about that night was that the rain was "very, very heavy. ". After that, he stayed in his hospital bed for two days.

Zhang Bing was one of the first patients at the Wembley Arena. There are plenty of details to be worked out about the sanctuary, where nearly a thousand people are expected to live together.

Run-in

At the shelter hospital, beds are separated by about 1 meter, a measure of patient privacy.

One meter, enough for a desk. The desks, which read "25 middle schools" , come from the nearby Wuhan No. twenty-five Middle School. The desk and the bed, about 2 meters long and 1 meter wide, make up the whole private space of a patient. Behind every hospital bed, there is a family's joys and sorrows.

This may be the hardest place to stand for discrimination, and no one is going to be treated any differently because of the virus. Around almost every desk, CT scans stand up and roll up.

The first day in the shelter was chaotic. The food is cold. The bathroom is filthy. It's cold in the shelter. There's no hot water to bathe in. Water machine nearby is full of water, someone to protect the shop on the express box, the results appear more dirty.

Some outlets don't have electricity, don't have a heating pad, and don't have a way to charge your phone. Zhang Bing understands people's anxiety. "My family has several elderly people in different hospitals, my wife is in isolation in the hotel and we can only communicate by mobile phone. This is the case for everyone. "

One nurse was still in the middle of her shift, and she was already crowded with patients. Some want to take medicine, some to toilet paper, hot water, constantly asked "there is no Wifi. ". One doctor said a patient came in, broke things and yelled to get out.

That night, a lot of people stayed up all night. In addition to anxiety, maladjustment, because the venue 24-hour light. Some patients go to nurses for antipsychotic drugs to fall asleep.

Liu Lianmei's biggest feeling is repression: Most people all day long stay in bed, with the quilt covered his head, not move at all. "I asked. They're not sick. They're just not in the mood. "

Two patients look at their mobile phones as they lie on their beds in the Shelter Hospital of Hongshan Stadium in Wuhan, China, on Feb. 21. China Youth Daily China Youth Net Trainee Reporter Lu Chong / photo

Confused and lying on the bed, Zhang Bing saw a garbage man, no protective clothing, hair is white. He realized that this man was also a patient. Then he thought, when he's better, he's going to help. After cleaning up, he also can not look past the boiling machine water, water bucket temporary storage of waste water, regular dumping.

Later, when he tried to dump the waste water, he found that it had already been poured. "You don't want to live in a mess... that's what people do, or you don't do it, and if one person comes forward, a lot of people do it. "

It started off in bits and pieces. Some helped the medics deliver medicine and distribute meals, and others helped to placate the new arrivals. Heard that the box generated in the garbage mixed milk and Porridge, not easy to burn treatment, some self-promotion and guidance for patients to do garbage classification, but also take turns in the trash can stand guard.

According to the geographical location, the cabin was divided into 8 areas, the shift to do health, according to the division of box lunch. The medical staff followed the lead and redrew the 5 zones, unified the names of the originally complicated 1,2, left and right zones into A-E zones, and elected the district chief to coordinate the work of each zone. Zhang Bing volunteered to become the district governor, also became the Temporary Party branch secretary of the Shelter Hospital.

Due to material constraints, the district chief's armband with ready-made "tobacco control counsellors" armband instead.

Someone found out that the patient did not eat lunch, asked, turned out to be from Hui people. All the districts need to figure out who has special dietary needs. From that night on, the Diet was halal, sugar-free and liquid.

It was also suggested that hundreds of people lived together and that in the event of a fire, the risks were high and fire training and drills were organized by those with fire-fighting knowledge among the patients. Five days later, the local fire department became aware of the problem and conducted fire training in each shelter.

Some of the mutual help is done through wechat groups. Someone forgot to bring hand cream, spoke to a group of patients and borrowed it a few minutes later; many couldn't sleep because of the stadium lights, and a friend of the district chief's outside bought an eye mask.

Taking into account the residents hastily moved into the Shelter Hospital, the staff bought in advance dental appliances, towels, sanitary towels, socks, slippers, warm clothes and other items, but also prepared a Thermos Cup. But in the wechat group, they found a blind spot: Nail Clippers, so quickly applied for 100 to be sent into the shelter.

Where the authorities can't take care of it, folk wisdom comes into play. In Wuhan, where the winters are rainy and sunny, thousands of clothes from nearly 800 patients need to be aired, and the slender items in the Shelter Hospital have been transformed into laundry poles. In order to facilitate watching the play, people with lunch boxes, fruit made into a bracket, save hands holding mobile phones, tablets of the hard work.

When Zhou Yuting, 21, entered the shelter on Feb. 9, it already had a hair dryer and a microwave oven. She quickly accepted life in the shelter, which she thought was "just a couple of beds. ". Later, the shelter has been equipped with oxygen machine, CT room.

According to the regulations, the Shelter Hospital only accepts the 18-65 year-old mild disease patient. But for the sake of humanity, there are also children who move in with their parents. A paediatrician has also been assigned to the Shelter Hospital.

Five days later, the shower was ready, but the line was long, and even the meal took half an hour. Taking a bath is one of the most worrying things for women in the shelter, Zhou Yuting will go around to see if there are many people.

Life

The day in the shelter begins at 6 a.m. Wake up Zhou Yuting, is the medical staff handed over the thermometer. Some older people also need to have their blood pressure checked.

After that, Zhou Yuting has to go back to bed and get up at 8:00 for breakfast. On the Lantern Festival, breakfast is Tangyuan. If she's not in the shelter, she usually goes to bed at 3:00 at night and gets up at noon.

After breakfast, Xiao Meng, 11, and Fu Qiao, 18, began attending classes online. This year, Fu Qiao's illness did not affect her confidence. "everyone attended classes remotely, and I did not suffer. " Xiao Meng worried that the solution given by the teacher in the next class who was in charge of recording the math class was not the same as that given by the math teacher in her own class.

Senior 3 student Fu Qiao's desk is filled with textbooks in the Shelter Hospital of Hongshan Gymnasium in Wuhan on Feb. 21. She writes the curriculum by hand on post-it notes and pastes it on a partition. Everyone had an apple and milk for dinner, and the patient in the next bed gave her her own. China Youth Daily China Youth Net Trainee Reporter Lu Chong / photo

The Wembley Arena lowered the frequency and volume of the broadcasts for the students, and the people around them spoke softly.

Fu Qiao felt that she was learning more effectively in the shelter, because there was always someone watching her back and reminding her to keep her back straight. Everyone put the box meal to her hand, help her perm Chinese medicine. At home, her parents have been "free-range" to her.

Recently, the medical staff of the Shelter Hospital set aside half of the doctor's Office for study. Fu Qiao said she could feel the doctor's office and in and out, trying to minimize the noise. Sometimes the doctor would sit on the other side of the room, resting his eyes, or pounding his legs as he answered messages. On February 23, a medical worker wrote "Fu Qiao refuels, the college entrance examination will be a success" on his protective suit.

After breakfast is the time for the doctor to make rounds and dispense medicine. Patients generally stay in their own beds, there is a problem, there is a need at this time. That way, when a shift of medics enters the shelter in the afternoon, they can bring in what they need.

Zhang Bing chose this time to contact his family. A 38-year-old teacher at a private school also runs classes according to the schedule, but he takes the form of a written class because the shelter is noisy and he doesn't want to attract the special attention of his students.

At 12:00 noon, the district chiefs will pick up lunch. The menu in the shelter is 120 yuan per day, plus fruit and milk. Xiao Meng and Fu Qiao always receive more copies from nearby patients.

Xiao Meng felt that, in the shelter than at home more happy, because "eat and drink not worry" . A nurse told the reporter that some patients do not want to leave the shelter, think here to eat well, still can go out for air. Some people even evade nucleic acid detection for this.

A patient eats dinner at the Shelter Hospital of Hongshan Gymnasium in Wuhan on Feb. 21. China Youth Daily China Youth Net Trainee Reporter Lu Chong / photo

Zhou Yuting was tired of eating in the shelter. She had never led such a healthy life, with a regular schedule, three vegetarian meals, fruit and milk.

Zhou Yuting likes spicy food. When she entered the shelter, her first order of errands was several packs of Turkey noodles. Half way through the meal, all the aunts and uncles in the neighborhood gathered around. People are hungry because they haven't eaten spicy food for so long.

"Too nutritious to live here, who does not want to eat some junk food? " In their commission, Zhou Yuting to the surrounding Shangchao Turkey face to buy out.

Because of the epidemic, she "escaped" the family reunion of the Spring Festival, but had to accept uncle aunt's "cross-examination" in the shelter: How is the paper written? Did you get a job? Are you in love?

Every day at 3:00 pm and 7:30 pm after dinner, each district organizes to do aerobics and square dancing. When it was time, District Mayor Zhang Bing took up the trumpet to mobilize everyone to participate. The oldest person in the shelter was an 83-year-old woman who sometimes followed suit. The reporter sees in the square cabin, a middle-aged man who soaks in the foot beside also stepped out the water splash along with the melody.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Gao Xiaoyan (right) , a nurse at the Huzhu Tu Autonomous County Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine, practices Baduanjin in the Shelter Hospital of Hongshan Gymnasium in Wuhan, China, Feb. 21. China Youth Daily China Youth Net Trainee Reporter Lu Chong / photo

Zhang Bing is keen to get bored young people to stop spending so much time lying in bed with their phones, or getting together in groups to play with them, but he rarely succeeds.

In the face of Zhang Bing's loudspeakers, Zhou Yuting first pretended not to hear, and then a time to get out of Hoida. Zhang Bing felt that this was also the achievement of his goal.

Chen rarely participates in these activities. He worries about his parents in his hometown of Huanggang, the village's "hard-core road closure, " "what if we don't have food or medicine? What if there's an accident and ambulances or fire trucks can't get in? " He also worries about his wife being infected at the quarantine point and doesn't report the bad news. He skyped with his wife every day, cheering each other up.

He spent a week in the shelter, flipping through his phone's address book. Well-connected classmates, friends, he called all over. In the shelter, smoke is scarce, but Chen Jun to find someone to beg, the other side will be generous to give.

He likes to step out of the shelter at night and look at the moon. "It's quiet during the day. " He sometimes thinks of his fellow patients in the hospital's intensive care unit. "I wonder if they've recovered. ". Sometimes he was lost in the moon.

A night like this is supposed to be a reunion. Late at night, there are patients in the outdoor spotlights and family video chat.

After finishing her homework, Xiao Meng will call her grandfather. GRANDPA is very painful small dream, small dream home after Cram School at night, a said hungry, GRANDPA will give her cooking. Xiao Meng was worried about her grandfather. "He was sick for a long time. When he called, he didn't say he wasn't feeling well, but I could hear that he had no energy to speak. "

At 11:30 p.m. , people fell asleep, and Fu Qiao couldn't study because her neighbors and doctors would urge her to go to bed early. In the shelter, she had dozens of "parents" and "homeroom teachers" .

Some patients don't get a good night's sleep until they're discharged. Zhou Yuting feel, with hundreds of people "together in a room" , very awkward, worried about their sleep phase is not good. Zhang Bing said that his face was covered with a mask and blindfold, so he would arrange a lot of things for himself during the day, tired a bit, and have a good rest at night.

When he first entered the shelter, Zhang Bing always woke up at night. The Dome Light of the Gymnasium threw him into a sort of trance, and he was enveloped in a sense of unreality. He had to rub his eyes for half a day, see clearly around someone asleep, someone playing mobile phones, up at night, a nurse walking, and feel warm, this just realized, in the shelter hospital, "mixed feelings. ".

Chen Jun always waited until everyone else was asleep, and secretly changed his intimate clothes in the quilt. But he thought it was good enough. In the intensive care unit, in order to facilitate rescue, there are patients naked, just covered with a quilt, or "wear" a blindfold, tied from the back of the "cloth.

But some people do not care about these, after washing clothes, underwear casually hanging in the bedside.

Crevices

At night, looking at hundreds of beds full of patients, Liu Lianmei heart is not the taste. "I always thought everyone was in trouble. I came here to take refuge. "

She makes her rounds every hour, and when she sees a patient's comforter drop to the floor, she helps cover it up. She thought of her sleeping son.

Liu Lianmei showed her son a photo of herself in a protective suit. "Mom, are you going to fight a monster? " The son asked in the video. "Yes, mom has eliminated many enemies, " Liu replied

It takes half an hour for her to put on her heavy gear and then enter the shelter through a dark clean-up area, a potentially contaminated area, and a semi-contaminated passageway. She had been trained repeatedly, but was nervous about seeing hundreds of patients.

For the first time, they're all facing hundreds of patients at once. "You can't talk to everyone for 10 minutes. The patient's been here a long time, and he's doing fine, so talking to the doctor is a basic requirement. When a patient calls you, it's not good for you not to communicate, but you go in when you need something, and you spend half an hour wearing a protective suit,"said Han Guang, a local doctor.

As a rule, doctors rarely get to know their patients personally. This time, they have left patients with Wechat, set up wechat groups, dozens of doctors outside can also share the work.

In order to facilitate communication inside and outside the cabin, Hu Sheng, a doctor at Hubei Provincial Cancer Hospital, brought his mobile phone into the cabin and did not take it out again. Later, he put his own iPad back in, and he wanted patients to see their doctor more clearly and less fearfully.

A few days later, the shelter was equipped with several working cell phones for the medical staff. Their experience was later learned by other shelter management teams.

Liu Is from outside the province, and her difficulties include understanding the Wuhan dialect. Most of the patients in the shelter were middle-aged and elderly people, many of whom could only speak dialects and needed local people who could speak Mandarin to help translate.

Once, Liu Lianmei's colleagues heard a quarrel and rushed to try to stop it. They asked Zhou Yuting, who was on the other side, "why are they quarreling again? " In fact, two middle-aged men were greeting each other, "how many yards are too early? " (when is breakfast?) Because the Wuhan dialect sounds fierce, she misunderstood.

Disputes occasionally occur in the shelter, mostly due to insubordination of patients, such as not cooperating with garbage classification, or to pour water into the water machine. In the laundry area, some people criticized the front of the people do not put the washing powder back, two people back in the shelter is still noisy, attracted a group of people to see the excitement.

These disputes let Liu Lianmei feel the breath of life, "shows here as home. " The first few days, shelter atmosphere depressed, broadcast jokes to ease the atmosphere. Only one aunt is very lively, pulling people to chat, and others joke Liu Lianmei grow tall, "you guess that it is a man and a woman. "

The turning point, she thought, was when the first patient was discharged from the shelter. "like the last darkness before the Dawn, there is confidence. "

She's more afraid of her patients'needs than her own. "A lot of people are ashamed and feel like they are bothering us in there, so they wait for US passively and seldom ask for it. "

Zhang Bing remember, the first time outside to send in Sanitary Napkins, 12 packets were immediately divided up. He realized it was a big problem, but everyone was too embarrassed to ask, and the next day he took it upon himself to report a demand for more bags.

A young man went to the bathroom and wet his shoes. He hesitated for a long time before asking the nurse for his slippers. Liu Lianmei remembers that the young man carefully explained why he needed slippers, took the slippers and explained again, repeatedly apologized, said the trouble of the nurse.

"actually he doesn't need to say so much. We won't judge his needs, and he shouldn't be ashamed of it, " Liu said.

Shame sometimes comes from society.

There have been reports not to Fang Lei and Xiaomeng alias, and even published Xiaomeng did not wear a mask photo. Xiao Meng classmate's parents called the school, asked the head teacher Xiao Meng is not a new pneumonia, also said that hope to start school after Xiao Meng suspended to school. The teacher then knew Xiao Meng and his family in the shelter hospital.

In her native village of Huangpi District, Ms. Fang said, there was talk of her illness. Fang Lei saw in the news that some places where she had done business before did not welcome Hubei People. There was also news that some places had rewards for reporting Hubei People.

February 21, Wuhan Hongshan Stadium Shelter Hospital, a patient and his family video chat. China Youth Daily China Youth Net Trainee Reporter Lu Chong / photo

Dream doesn't know anything about this. To the shelter hospital, and she told six of her best friends. "They all encouraged me and told me to refuel and said it would be OK, " one of them told Xiao Meng. One of them also told Xiao Meng that the school had arranged for students to record videos to be played in the shelter hospital. She quit because she wanted to visit Xiao Meng directly in the shelter.

Zhou Yuting and Fu Qiao took the initiative to tell the students in the shelter hospital, they did not feel embarrassed. Zhou Yuting will also take photos of the food in the shelter to his classmates every day. "I eat better than them all. ". She said that the students are very interested in the shelter, often sent pictures and videos about the shelter hospital, asked whether it is true, the shelter in the facilities are good.

Good-bye

Now, Zhang Bing and Zhou Yuting have been discharged from the hospital. Chen Jun repeated several nucleic acid test results between negative and positive. If two consecutive nucleic acid tests are negative, and there are no obvious symptoms of respiratory tract, he will also be discharged.

Before leaving the hospital, Zhang Bing handed over the armband of his district chief, the work manual of the Temporary Party branch and the party flag, and urged the attention of daily work. The enthusiastic middle-aged man did not retreat the size of the Shelter Hospital Group, see the patients need supplies, he helped to coordinate.

A doctor told reporters that in recent days, the number of people discharged from the hospital every day here are about 50, the number of people admitted to the hospital is about 30, began to appear "bed and other people" situation.

Ten years ago, Liu Lianmei visited Wuhan. This time to Wuhan, she took a bus in the evening peak through Xiongchu Avenue, all the way to see the most is the rapid passing of the ambulance.

Wuhan has many more skyscrapers than it did 10 years ago, but the sight of an empty city made her feel bleak. "The city is really in big trouble, " she wrote in her diary that day.

A nurse from the Guangxi medical team, who arrived the same day, said many colleagues cried as they sat on buses and saw the empty city. Liu Lianmei looked forward to the day when the Wembley Arena would close.

Fang Lei hopes the epidemic will soon be over. She's a pillar of the family, traveling all the time for the clothing business. In 2017, she was in a car accident and suffered multiple fractures. She was only in bed for a month before she went back to work.

She read little, hard life, she hoped that small dream no longer follow their old road, to small dream the best training excellent class.

Xiao Meng said she wanted to go to a girls'party when the epidemic was over. She missed all the previous parties because she had to go to a training class.

February 14 is the wedding anniversary of Liu Lianmei and her husband. This Valentine's Day, two people thousands of miles apart sent each other a text message to express their love, they wrote in the text, "this is a special year. ".

Since February 19, more new cases have been diagnosed in the country each day. Hospitals in Wuhan are reopening emergency and outpatient clinics, and getting back on track.

1 March. Wuhan Qiao Estuary Martial Arts Square cabin has taken the lead in the "rest cabin" , in due course, other square-cabin hospitals will also be "closed. ". Patients, health care workers, sanitation workers, security guards, and volunteers all return to a normal life.

Chen Jun met two neighbors in the shelter that he did not know before. He grew up in the old town, and the whole street knew him. But ever since we moved into the apartment building, the neighbors have barely seen each other.

Chen Jun just went to the shelter hospital, not familiar with the environment, nearby patients are very warm, take his rice, take fruit, tell him where hot water, where more quiet, beds next to a few people quickly familiar with. Ask, Chen Jun discovers to have 2 people and oneself live very close. Unified take patients out of the shelter to go home on the bus, Zhou Yuting also found that the same car there are 10 people and their own community.

They passed each other in the shelter.

Fang Lei and Xiao Meng went by pseudonyms to protect their privacy

(Lu Chong, a trainee reporter for the CYB's website, contributed to this report.)
